  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT203-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">vāyilākap pukka tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ colliyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by HER to the confidante when she enters as a
          mediator.</p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT203">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>malaiyiṭai yiṭṭa nāṭṭaru mallar</l>
          <l>marantalai tōṉṟā vūraru mallar</l>
          <l>kaṇṇiṟ kāṇa naṇṇuvaḻi yiruntuṅ</l>
          <l>kaṭavu ṇaṇṇiya pālōr pōla</l>
          <l>vorīi yoḻuku meṉṉaikkup</l>
          <l>pariyaleṉ maṉyāṉ paṇṭoru kālē.</l>

        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>One time, formerly, I was indeed in distress<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">
            pariyaleṉ</term> is a semantically and morphologically ambiguous form. It can either be
            1st sg. neg. of the root pari-tal or 1st sg. denominative of the verbal noun pariyal.
            The verb pari is split in DEDR into several homonyms, among which at least DEDR 3964 "to
            be affectionate" and 3965 "to be troubled, distressed, suffer" are possible. In other
            words, we have several possible statements (6b-d), and perhaps such an emotive
            elusiveness is precisely what is intended here.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">for my lord who is<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">orīi oḻukum</term>:
            is this to be understood as a coordination ("who abandons [me and] goes") or does<term xml:lang="ta">oḻuku</term>function as an auxiliary of a continuous present?
            Alternatively it is possible to relate oḻukum to a second root<term xml:lang="ta">
            oḻuku-tal</term> "to act according to the law" (DEDR 1011), which would in quite well
            with the topos of HIS dutifully leaving HER (5b).</note> renouncing [me],</l>
          <l rend="indent2">like one whose fate is placed in god,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṭavuḷ naṇṇiya pālōr</term>: this phrase is sociologically difficult.
            The verb <term xml:lang="ta">naṇṇu-tal</term> usually denotes a spacial situation of
            something (as to be seen in line 3,<term xml:lang="ta">naṇṇu vaḻi</term>). Here it must
            be used in a transferred sense. So literally the phrase might mean "one (h.)/those whose
            fate is attached to god". Does this refer to someone who has given up worldly
            attachments?</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">although there was a way near [enough] for the eye to see,</l>
          <l rend="indent">and he is not from a village of which the tree-tops are not visible,</l>
          <l rend="indent">and he is not from a country cut off by mountains.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">malai
            iṭaiyiṭṭa</term> literally presumably refers to mountains which are set between HER place and
            his country. The TL lexicalises iṭaiyiṭu as "to intervene; to interpose".</note></l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="5b">
            <l>for my lord who acts according to the law in abandoning [me],</l>
          </lg>
          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6b">
            <l>One time, formerly, I indeed felt affection</l>
          </lg>
          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6c">
            <l>One time, formerly, I was indeed not distressed</l>
          </lg>
          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6d">
            <l>One time, formerly, I indeed didn't feel affection</l>
          </lg>
        </lg>

      </div>
